column1: A ball is thrown up and after 2 sec it reached the ground. What will be the maximum height?
column4:

\[
t=\left(2 v_{i} \sin \theta\right) / g

projectile
putting $t=2 s$
\[
\begin{array}{l}
(2 \times 9.8) / 2=v_{i} \sin \theta \\
v_{i} \sin \theta=9.8
\end{array}
\]
We also know that
\[
\mathrm{h}=\mathrm{v}_{\mathrm{i}}^{2}\left(\sin ^{2} \theta\right) / 2 \mathrm{g}
\]
$\mathrm{h}$ is the height of projectile

$\mathrm{h}=4.9 \mathrm{m}$

If the wavelength of two light is $\lambda=4000$ A and $\lambda=5000$ A is used in optical instrument.

column4:
We know that
\[
\mathrm{R}=\mathrm{D} / 1.22 \lambda
\]
$\mathrm{R}$ is the resolution, $\mathrm{D}$ is the diameter, $\lambda$ is the wavelength
$\mathrm{R} \propto 1 / \lambda$
\begin{aligned}
&\mathrm{R} \propto 1 / \lambda\\
&\mathrm{R}=\mathrm{constant} / \lambda\\
&\mathrm{R} 1 / \mathrm{R} 2=\lambda 2 / \lambda 1\\
&\lambda 2=5000 \mathrm{A}\\
&\lambda 1=4000 \mathrm{A}\\
&\lambda 2 / \lambda 1=5 / 4\\
&\mathrm{R} 1 / \mathrm{R} 2=5 / 4
\end{aligned}

Electric potential due to $-q$ on point $A$

\]
Net Electric potential
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\mathrm{E}=\mathrm{V}_{2}+\mathrm{V}_{1}=(2 \mathrm{kq} / \mathrm{d})-(\mathrm{kq} / 2 \mathrm{d}) \\
\mathrm{E}=(\mathrm{kq} / \mathrm{d})(2-(1 / 2)) \\
\mathrm{E}=(\mathrm{kq} / \mathrm{d})(3 / 2) \\
\mathrm{E}=3 \mathrm{kq} / 2 \mathrm{d}
\end{array}
\]

\[

\]
Now
\[
\begin{array}{l}
\mathrm{n}=1+\left(\mathrm{R}_\mathrm{g} / \mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{s}}\right) \\
\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{s}}=\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{g}} /\left(\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{g}} / \mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{s}}\right)=\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{s}}
\end{array}
\]
Also,
\[
\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{s}}=\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{g}} \mathrm{R} / \mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{s}}
\]
